          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829241?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年 5 月，土耳其支持的一名宪兵在叙利亚西北部据报道被阿布·侯赛因·古莱希 (Abu al-Husayn al-Qurayshi) 使用的房屋外站岗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Bakr Alkasem/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108092"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 2:57 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伊斯坦布尔——伊斯兰国周四证实，其鲜为人知的最高领导人已被杀，这是该极端组织的高级领导人在不到两年的时间里第三次遭遇这种命运。</p><p>该组织在其发言人的一份音频声明中表示，其前任领导人代号阿布·侯赛因·古莱希 (Abu al-Husayn al-Qurayshi) 在与控制叙利亚西北部部分地区的敌对武装组织沙姆解放组织 (Hayat Tahrir al-Sham) 的冲突中身亡。 。</p><p>几个月前，土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-leader-killed-in-intelligence-operation-turkeys-erdogan-says-93f844cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，伊斯兰国领导人在土耳其在叙利亚北部的一次情报行动中被打死</a>。</p><p>该组织任命了新领导人阿布·哈夫斯·哈希米·古莱希 (Abu Hafs al-Hashimi al-Qurayshi)。据极端主义专家称，该组织的最新任最高指挥官在负责该组织期间没有发表公开声明。</p><p> 2014年，“伊斯兰国”控制了伊拉克和叙利亚大片地区，对数百万人实施残酷的宗教统治，并在全球范围内发起针对平民的暴力袭击行动。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>经过伊拉克和叙利亚军队在美国空军支持下多年的压倒性军事行动后，该组织于 2019 年失去了对叙利亚最后一块领土的控制。</p><p>该组织一直是一个地下激进组织，仍然有能力实施致命暴力。 2022 年初，其武装分子在叙利亚东部越狱，导致与美国支持的叙利亚军队进行了数天的巷战。大约 500 人在暴力事件中死亡。</p><p>伊斯兰国已无法重拾昔日在叙利亚和伊拉克的势头，但也在阿富汗和非洲部分地区设有分支机构。</p><p>该组织仍然面临着美国领导的叙利亚和伊拉克联军的压力。 7月，美国军方表示，他们在叙利亚的一次空袭中打死了一名伊斯兰国领导人。</p><p>该组织的前任高级领导人于 2022 年在一次与美国无关的行动中被叙利亚武装分子杀害。另一名高级领导人于 2022 年初在美国突击队的一次突袭中被杀。</p><p>写信给 Jared Malsin： <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.malsin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 18:57:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3<author><![CDATA[Jared Malsin]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What Is Happening in Niger? What to Know About the Coup]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国西非反恐盟友民选总统下台引发军事干预威胁<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829069/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="军政府政变的支持者在尼日尔首都尼亚美集会。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>军政府政变的支持者在尼日尔首都尼亚美集会。法新社/盖蒂图片社<span>法新社/盖蒂图片社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107681"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107681"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 2:34（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>尼日尔精锐总统卫队官员上周<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拘留了这个西非国家的民选总统</a>穆罕默德·巴祖姆，并宣布自己为该国新领导人。这次政变令美国和欧洲政府感到震惊，这些国家一直与巴祖姆和尼日尔军队密切合作，打击非洲萨赫勒地区的伊斯兰武装分子。</p><p>尼日尔的一些西非邻国（主要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与美国和欧洲结盟</a>）威胁要使用武力恢复巴祖姆的地位。其他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯结盟的</a>国家则表示，他们将捍卫尼日尔的新军政府。</p><h3>美国和欧洲政府为何担心尼日尔政变？</h3><p>尼日尔一直是美国和欧洲<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">打击基地组织和伊斯兰国武装分子</a>的中心，这些武装分子近年来在撒哈拉以南的半干旱地区萨赫勒地区杀害了数千人。在马里和布基纳法索军方领导的政府驱逐了一直在那里与伊斯兰叛乱分子作战的法国和其他西方军队后，尼日尔变得更加重要。美国已花费约 5 亿美元武装尼日尔军队，配备从帐篷、收音机到侦察机和装甲运兵车等各种装备。美国在尼日尔驻有约 1,100 名士兵，他们训练当地特种部队并为他们执行任务提供建议。法国在尼日尔驻有大约 1,500 名士兵。</p><p>欧盟还依赖世界上最贫穷国家之一的尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-considers-substantial-fund-for-africa-to-deal-with-migrants-1440871414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来阻止非洲移民</a>进入利比亚并从那里进入欧盟。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="819" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828956?width=1260&amp;height=819" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">政变支持者在尼亚美示威期间悬挂俄罗斯国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>什么是西共体？它能扭转政变吗？</h3><p>西非国家经济共同体是一个由 15 个西非国家组成的政治和经济组织，其中包括尼日利亚、加纳和塞内加尔等地区重量级国家。周日，西非经共体领导人在一次紧急峰会上给尼日尔新军政府规定了 7 天的期限，以释放巴祖姆并让他重新担任总统。此后，该组织领导人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁要对尼日尔发动军事干预</a>，以恢复巴祖姆的权力。他们还对尼日尔实施了一系列严厉的金融和贸易制裁，希望迫使军政府做出让步。这些制裁包括冻结尼日尔在地区中央银行的资产以及切断尼日利亚的电力供应。尼日尔约 70% 的电力从尼日利亚购买。</p><p>作为回应，马里和布基纳法索的政变也受到西非经共体的谴责，它们警告说，他们将把对尼日尔的武装干预视为宣战，并将保卫尼亚美军政府。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828965?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲和美国公民从尼日尔撤离后抵达罗马附近的机场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：雷莫·卡西利/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>美国如何回应？</h3><p>拜登总统和国务卿安东尼·布林肯呼吁释放巴祖姆并保护尼日尔的民主。然而，美国官员一直小心翼翼地避免将军方的行动称为政变，这一名称将引发美国法律<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对军事援助的限制</a>。国防部表示，没有计划将军事人员或装备撤出尼日尔，并支持通过外交途径解决局势。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=2AE037D3-6705-43B5-828C-C117387FADDD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尼日尔上周发生政变后，欧洲各国政府和美国下令从尼日尔撤离本国公民。军政府领导人表示，军方不会屈服于压力，要求让被罢黜的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆复职。照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>拜登政府尚未表示美国是否会为西非经共体可能对尼日尔进行的军事干预提供后勤或其他支持。 “我们支持西非经共体的努力，包括施加压力，”布林肯周四表示。美国国务院已下令<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">撤离美国驻尼亚美大使馆的所有非必要人员</a>以及美国大使馆工作人员的家属。</p><p>与法国不同的是，美国尚未从尼日尔全面撤离美国公民。法国本周向尼日尔派遣了多架撤侨航班，并表示已帮助约 40 名美国公民离开该国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828970?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆与美国和欧洲政府密切合作，打击伊斯兰激进分子。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路透社/媒体库</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3><strong>俄罗斯对尼日尔政变持何立场？</strong></h3><p>俄罗斯政府呼吁尼日尔恢复宪法秩序，并警告不要进行武装干预。叶夫根尼·普里戈任,</p>他的准军事瓦格纳集团已经在马里拥有战士，他赞扬了这次政变，并向尼亚美军政府提供了雇佣军服务。<p></p><p>法国外交部长本周将周末针对法国大使馆的支持政变抗议活动归咎于俄罗斯的虚假信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="390" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829050?width=700&amp;height=390" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">军政府首脑、尼日尔自称领导人奥马尔·查尼将军率领总统卫队发动了政变。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ORTN/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>奥马尔·奇亚尼将军是谁？</h3><p>奥马尔·齐亚尼将军，有时也被称为阿卜杜拉哈马内，是发动反对巴祖姆起义的总统卫队队长。他现在作为尼日尔自封的领导人领导军政府。据熟悉尼日尔局势的人士透露，巴祖姆一直在考虑是否解雇蒂亚尼，这是政变的触发因素之一。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——威廉·莫尔丁对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟 (Gabriele Steinhauser)，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 18:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc<author><![CDATA[Gabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>奥马尔·齐亚尼</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[India Restricts Laptop Imports to Boost Local Manufacturing]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该国笔记本电脑销售的很大一部分依赖进口，其中许多来自竞争对手中国<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107307"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828990?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">印度此举被视为旨在说服更多全球电子制造商签署其“印度制造”计划。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：普拉卡什·辛格/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107307"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rajesh-roy" itemprop="url" rel="author">拉杰什·罗伊</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 11:43 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-restricts-laptop-imports-to-boost-local-manufacturing-244cf56a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>新德里——政府和行业官员表示，印度正在加大进口笔记本电脑、平板电脑和其他消费电子设备的难度，此举旨在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-u-s-and-modi-rewire-indian-defense-and-tech-dfabec47?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">促进当地制造业</a>并解决一些安全问题。</p><p>印度商业和工业部周四表示，笔记本电脑和其他个人计算设备的进口现在需要许可证，这使得进口过程变得更加繁琐。</p><p> “其中一些进口产品的硬件安全性令人担忧。因此，为了印度的数字安全利益，我们采取了这一步骤。”一位直接了解此事的印度政府官员表示。 “这样做的后果也可能是这些公司开始考虑本地制造。”</p><p>人们普遍认为此举旨在让更多的全球电子产品制造商加入该国的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-offers-1-billion-in-perks-to-entice-computer-makers-from-china-11614171742?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“印度制造”计划</a>，该计划为本地制造电子产品和其他高科技产品提供激励，符合条件的公司将收回数百万美元的投资。该国最初将该计划针对智能手机，后来将其扩展到其他领域，包括无人机<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foxconn-abandons-india-chip-venture-with-vedanta-e11a8687?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">、半导体</a>以及科技硬件。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>根据官方数据，2022 年 1 月至 12 月，新限制范围内的计算机和服务器等计算设备的进口总额接近 100 亿美元，约占印度去年进口总额的 1.4%。</p><p>印度目前没有知名的本地个人电脑制造商，而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HPQ" class="company-name">惠普</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DELL" class="company-name">戴尔科技</a>等跨国公司目前在当地的生产数量有限。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a>通过其合同制造商在印度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-opens-its-first-retail-store-in-india-7f3a7035?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">生产越来越多的 iPhone</a> ，但尚未在该国生产<span class="company-name-type">MacBook</span>或 iPad。</p><p> Counterpoint Research 总监塔伦·帕塔克 (Tarun Pathak) 表示，印度在智能手机和电视几乎 100% 本地制造方面取得了显着进展，但在 IT 硬件领域，约三分之二的销售额依赖进口。</p><p>戴尔根据该计划的早期版本申请了获得本地笔记本电脑制造奖励的资格。今年 5 月，政府将用于制造 IT 硬件的资金扩大到约 20 亿美元，涵盖笔记本电脑、平板电脑、一体化个人电脑和服务器，以期与更多跨国公司签约。本周，它将制造商根据该计划提出申请的截止日期延长至 8 月 30 日。</p><p>印度还出台了关税或其他进口限制的激励措施，行业高管和分析师表示，鉴于许多类型的电子产品和零部件的本地制造尚未扩大规模，这可能会影响制造商和消费者。</p><p> “这是政府的下意识反应。工业界正陷入困境。他们应该首先与我们进行一些协商，而不是立即限制进口，”一家也销售平板电脑和笔记本电脑的领先消费电子公司的高管表示。 “这将影响业务连续性。”</p><p> Counterpoint 的帕塔克表示，这些限制可能会在短期内导致供应中断，尤其是随着节日购物季的临近。Counterpoint 的数据显示，印度年度个人电脑市场规模约为 80 亿美元。</p><p>惠普引领印度个人电脑销售市场，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LNVGY" class="company-name">联想</a>紧随其后</p>根据市场研究公司 IDC 的数据，中国。印度近年来一直寻求减少对竞争对手中国的进口依赖，特别是在 2020 年 6 月两国有争议的喜马拉雅边境爆发暴力冲突、造成 20 名印度士兵和 4 名中国士兵死亡之后。<p></p><p>官员和行业高管表示，激励计划已经促进了印度科技制造业的发展。 4月至6月的贸易数据显示，尽管整体出口下降，但电子产品出口（尤其是智能手机）大幅增长。</p><p>写信给 Rajesh Roy，邮箱： <a href="mailto:rajesh.roy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rajesh.roy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 15:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-restricts-laptop-imports-to-boost-local-manufacturing-244cf56a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-restricts-laptop-imports-to-boost-local-manufacturing-244cf56a<author><![CDATA[Rajesh Roy]]></author><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>便携式电脑</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>技术</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业/行业进口</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>戴尔科技集团 C</category><category>戴尔</category><category>联想集团</category><category>0992.HK</category><category>港币:992</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>公司的</category><category>工业进口</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>营销</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>便携式电脑</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Rags-to-Riches Female Candidate Shakes Up Mexico Presidential Race]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>小时候卖玉米粉蒸肉的索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 与总统洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔 (López Obrador) 发生争执，并为沮丧的反对派提供鼓励<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828458/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="霍奇特尔·加尔维斯最近在蒂华纳竞选，在墨西哥反对派联盟总统提名的竞选中处于领先地位。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>霍奇特尔·加尔韦斯最近在蒂华纳竞选，在墨西哥反对派联盟总统提名的竞选中处于领先地位。桑迪·赫法克 (Sandy Huffaker) 供职于《华尔街日报》<span>桑迪·赫法克 (Sandy Huffaker) 供职于《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105162"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105162"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jose-decordoba" itemprop="url" rel="author">何塞·德·科尔多瓦</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/juan-montes" itemprop="url" rel="author">胡安·蒙特斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>墨西哥库埃纳瓦卡——Xóchitl Gálvez 穿着长及脚踝的传统土著服饰，大步走进挤满人的礼堂，商界人士起立鼓掌，高呼“Xóchitl”！霍奇特尔！</p><p>自 6 月参加墨西哥总统竞选以来，60 岁的加尔韦斯似乎让沮丧的反对派兴奋不已，并使总统安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔感到不安，他的执政党莫雷纳党预计将在明年的总统选举中轻松获胜，凭借民众的支持领导的燕尾服。</p><p>几周之内，加尔韦斯就将自己定位为十几个赢得墨西哥反对派联盟提名的候选人中明显的领跑者。候选人将于 9 月 3 日初选后确定。</p><p>洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔不再参选是因为<strong>&nbsp;</strong>墨西哥不允许连任。他很可能会祝福墨西哥城前市长克劳迪娅·谢因鲍姆，后者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexican-presidential-hopefuls-kick-off-race-to-succeed-lopez-obrador-70b16467?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">有望赢得党内提名</a>。在民意调查中，她领先莫雷纳的另一位希望之星、前外交部长马塞洛·埃布拉德(Marcelo Ebrard)约10个百分点。</p><p>反对派选民<strong>&nbsp;</strong>在加尔韦斯介入之前，他已经接受了莫雷纳在 2024 年选举中取得压倒性胜利。</p><p>这位鲜为人知的参议员经常骑着电动自行车出行，她有一个引人入胜的个人故事，从年轻女孩的街头小贩成长为成功的女商人和当选官员。她的支持者说，她传达的妇女权利、支持墨西哥人民对美好生活的渴望以及民族团结的信息，给因洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的分裂政治而疲惫不堪的墨西哥人带来了希望。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="816" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828495?width=1260&amp;height=816" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Xóchitl Gálvez 骑着自行车游览墨西哥城。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿尔弗雷多·埃斯特雷拉/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828461?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 的平易近人的举止、朴实的语言和对戏剧手势的喜爱吸引了普通墨西哥人。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的桑迪·赫法克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>墨西哥政治分析人士表示，加尔韦斯最近在民调中的支持率上升很大程度上要归功于洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔本人，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/think-u-s-politics-is-exhausting-mexicos-president-has-a-news-conference-every-morning-11565626849?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">每天都在早间新闻发布会上猛烈抨击她</a>，嘲笑她自力更生的故事，并提高了她在全国的知名度。</p><p>民意调查专家尤利塞斯·贝尔特兰 (Ulises Beltrán) 表示：“她是一个引人注目的现象。”他指出，她以两位数的优势领先最接近的反对派竞争者。</p><p>洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的发言人否认总统在政治上提振了加尔维斯，并将她的崛起归因于媒体的有利报道。他拒绝对总统竞选发表评论。</p><p>正在寻求提名的执政党成员、前参议员里卡多·蒙雷亚尔表示，洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔发表有关加尔韦斯的言论是为了动员他的政治基础。</p><p> “他把差异说得一清二楚是正确的，”他说。</p><p>虽然加尔韦斯作为一名女商人的成功吸引了墨西哥的政治和经济机构，但她平易近人的举止、朴实的语言和对戏剧手势的喜爱却赢得了普通墨西哥人的青睐。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/3e8d3948-b604-4789-979f-3b0c2356e368.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xbgzW1zoD8k" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">她戴着银色假发，头戴白色瓜亚贝拉，在 2018 年的一段视频中模仿了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔</a>，该视频在 YouTube 上获得了数万次观看。去年，她穿着绿色霸王龙服装冲进参议院，抗议洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔提议的选举改革，她说这将使墨西哥“回到侏罗纪时代”。</p><p>加尔韦斯（Gálvez）的名字 Xóchitl 发音为“SOH-cheel”，在纳瓦特尔语中意为“花”，他的父亲是土著奥托米人，母亲是混血儿妇女，出生在特帕佩克（Tepatepec）。特帕佩克是一个昏昏欲睡的小镇，约有 11,000 人，周围环绕着郁郁葱葱的玉米地，车程约两小时。 &#39; 从墨西哥城开车过来。</p><p>加尔维斯说，她酗酒的父亲（现已去世）经常殴打她的母亲，有一次威胁要用猎枪射击母亲后，半夜将妻子和女儿赶出了家门。</p><p>她的表弟拉蒙·加尔韦斯 (Ramón Gálvez) 说，小时候，她与父母和四个兄弟姐妹睡在距离镇主广场几个街区的一栋单层土坯房的同一个房间里。房子没有自来水，一家人不得不收集雨水。他们与住在另外两个房间的七名亲戚共用一个厕所。</p><p> “这是一种充满暴力和贫困的生活，”她说。加尔维斯说，为了维持生计，她帮助母亲在街上卖果冻和玉米粉蒸肉。她说，当她父亲反对她读六年级以上时，她反抗了他。</p><p> “如果有什么东西定义了她，那就是她渴望变得更好，”表弟马可·安东尼奥·鲁伊斯说。</p><p> 17 岁时，加尔韦斯离开特帕佩克，来到墨西哥城贫民区的一间金属板搭建的单间小屋。她在接受采访时说，她早上担任电话接线员，晚上在墨西哥国立自治大学学习工程学，并在那里获得了奖学金。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="814" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828562?width=1260&amp;height=814" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">总统安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的政党有望赢得下次选举。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：isaac esquivel/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="805" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828463?width=1260&amp;height=805" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 的一位支持者在最近的一次竞选集会上举着一块牌子，上面写着“Xambeadora”，这是墨西哥“勤奋者”一词与她名字的组合。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的桑迪·赫法克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>由于对计算的着迷，她创立了一家为智能建筑提供设备的高科技公司。 1999年，她被列入世界经济论坛的100位未来全球领导人名单。第二年，猎头公司向总统文森特·福克斯推荐她领导一个土著事务研究所，她一直担任到 2006 年。</p><p> 2018 年，她成为保守派国家行动党 (PAN) 的参议员，尽管她不是党员。</p><p> “她的人生故事超越了墨西哥国家故事的任何戏剧性剧本，”参议员同事、国家行动党前主席古斯塔沃·马德罗说。</p><p>民意调查专家贝尔特兰表示，加尔韦斯作为候选人的优势在于，她颠覆了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔对反对派的讽刺，认为后者代表了富裕、腐败和保守的寡头政治。</p><p> “信息就是信使，”政治分析家、墨西哥前外交部长豪尔赫·卡斯塔涅达 (Jorge Castañeda) 说。 “她让洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的身份政治对他有利。”</p><p>民意调查专家亚历杭德罗·莫雷诺表示，加尔韦斯还吸引了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔政党的传统选民。 “她对女性、老年人和受教育程度较低的人很有吸引力，”他说。</p><p>尽管如此，在 El Financiero 报纸最近的一项民意调查中，加尔维斯仍落后 Sheinbaum 10 个百分点。</p><p>加尔维斯表示，她支持总统的社会计划，但认为这些计划应该更加有效。她认为自己的个人故事是对洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔对像她这样的墨西哥奋斗者的蔑视的谴责。</p><p>在总统透露了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔公司合同的财务数据后，加尔韦斯对洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔提起了两项刑事诉讼。她说这些数据包括机密的税务信息，她说这些信息是非法获得的。洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔没有透露它来自哪里。他的发言人表示，法官将确定洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔是否做了不当或非法的事情。</p><p>加尔维斯偶尔会用墨西哥俚语和咯咯的笑声来反驳洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的攻击。</p><p> “他是个大男子主义，我一生中和很多大男子主义打过交道，”她说。</p><p>六月，在他错误地表示她想拿走老人的养老金后，她要求他道歉。在他拒绝后，她向法院提起诉讼，并获得裁决，赋予她在同一论坛上作出答复的权利。</p><p> “我不会在战斗中退缩。当他向我提出质疑时，我就上了法庭，”她说。</p><p>拿着法院命令，加尔维斯骑着自行车前往总统府，洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔正在那里举行上午的新闻发布会。她敲了敲宫殿的厚重木门，但总统拒绝让她进去。加尔韦斯最终离开了。</p><p>她的失败尝试赢得了大批支持，促使她认真考虑竞选总统。两周后，她宣布参选。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828487?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">索奇特尔·加尔韦斯关于妇女权利、支持苦苦挣扎的墨西哥人对美好生活的渴望以及民族团结的信息引起了一些墨西哥人的共鸣。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡洛斯·莫雷诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 José de Córdoba <a href="mailto:jose.decordoba@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(jose.decordoba@wsj.com)</a>和 Juan Montes ( <a href="mailto:juan.montes@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">juan.montes@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86<author><![CDATA[José de CórdobaJuan Montes]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>家庭暴力</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>霍奇特尔·加尔韦斯</category><category>安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>家庭暴力</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[In Saudi Arabia’s Ukraine Peace Talks, How to Measure Success?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>围绕吉达会谈的问题包括谁将出席，以及与会者是否会就和平峰会的日期达成一致<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107221"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="564" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828857?width=860&amp;height=564" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">沙特阿拉伯王储穆罕默德·本·萨勒曼定于本周末就乌克兰和俄罗斯之间的和平举行会谈。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107221"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦斯·诺曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 9:58 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-saudi-arabias-ukraine-peace-talks-how-to-measure-success-fedb58ea"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>来自多达 30 个国家的高级官员将于本周末在沙特阿拉伯吉达举行会议，讨论<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-to-host-ukraine-peace-talks-as-part-of-western-effort-to-woo-global-south-244f03f0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰的和平问题</a>，但这不会是一次典型的和平会议。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-and-allies-plan-peace-summit-without-russia-72341551?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯不会在那里</a>。这个想法并不是要为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-ukraines-deadly-drones-putins-invasion-and-bidens-limits-5f2f2cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰和俄罗斯之间未来的和平协议</a>应该是什么样子提出规定性条款。预计沙特东道主不会在沟通结果方面做太多事情。截至周四，他们甚至还没有公开证实该事件正在发生。</p><p>尽管如此，此次会议是一个潜在重要进程的一部分，乌克兰及其西方支持者希望这一进程能够与重要的发展中国家制定一套共同原则，以制定对基辅有利的未来和平谈判。 Many of those developing countries, such as Brazil, India and South Africa, have been largely neutral on the war.</p><p> Ukraine and European officials hope the process will lead to a major peace summit where the participants can sign off a shared vision of how the war should end.</p><p> Russian officials sent mixed signals this week about how they see the process, which started with a late-June meeting in Denmark. The Kremlin said it would be watching closely while Russian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Maria Zakharova called the gathering a “hoax.”</p><p> Here are some of the issues on which Ukraine and its backers will judge whether the Jeddah meeting is a success:</p><h3> Who turns up?</h3><p> Ukraine and Saudi Arabia sent invitations last week to around 30 countries, double the number of capitals that participated in June&#39;s Copenhagen meeting. Some countries may dial in rather than turn up.</p><p> The US and several European countries—including Britain, France, Germany and Poland—are expected to be there. So are South Africa, Turkey, India and Brazil. But there are doubts about how many developing countries will come and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">big question surrounding China</a> . Beijing ignored the Copenhagen talks, but US and European officials said this week that China appeared likely to send a representative to Jeddah. As Russia&#39;s most important foreign ally, China is seen as crucial to build traction behind the talks.</p><h3> Path to peace summit?</h3><p> The meeting will be seen as a major success if it produces a declaration at the end with a specific set of shared principles for framing peace talks and sets a date for the peace summit that Ukraine hopes to host this year. People involved in the process had talked down the likelihood of either of those happening, but a senior European diplomat said on Thursday that these goals aren&#39;t impossible.</p><h3> The Zelensky peace formula?</h3><p> The extent to which the talks embrace parts of President Volodymyr Zelensky&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/ukraine-zelensky-biden-congress-washington-trip-russia/card/zelensky-says-biden-supports-his-peace-plan-niPc0HGjRkabUKS9mL5A?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">10-point peace plan</a> will be key. Diplomats said Ukraine pressed for broad backing for its plan at the Copenhagen meeting, and the key developing countries said that wasn&#39;t going to happen. A particular sticking point: Ukraine&#39;s call for all Russian troops to withdraw before peace talks can start is seen as an obstacle to peace by some countries.</p><p> European officials say they hope to use the Ukraine plan—which also deals with prisoners of war, nuclear safety and food and energy security—to frame the issues in Jeddah. They would be eager to see working groups of the participants discuss each of the points in more detail at some point. But they warn that whatever eventually emerges from the talks will likely be a list of key principles of international law that everyone can embrace: support for territorial sovereignty and integrity, the application of international law, and the need for conflict to be resolved through dialogue and not the use or threat of force.</p><h3> Russia home alone?</h3><p> From the start, Ukraine and its Western backers were <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/changing-places-europeans-grow-more-assertive-on-ukraine-as-washington-shows-caution-e4b83acf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">clear that Russia wouldn&#39;t be invited</a> . They wanted to build support among developing countries for a durable and fair peace, which they believe should favor Ukraine as a victim of the Russian invasion. However, Western diplomats acknowledge that, at some point, if the talks are to lead to something, there will need to be eventual negotiations between Ukraine and Russia.</p><p> According to people involved in the talks, several developing countries questioned the absence of Russia in Copenhagen. Mexican President</p> Andrés Manuel López Obrador said this week his country would only participate in Jeddah if Russia was there. The extent of pressure from developing countries to bring Russia on board soon will be important.<p></p><h3> Western unity?</h3><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-nato-summit-membership-fb0d863a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Last month&#39;s NATO summit</a> underscored that even when only Ukraine and its Western backers are in the room, sparks can fly, with Zelensky initially denouncing a NATO communiqué that offered no clear path for Ukraine to join the alliance.</p><p> Tensions between Ukraine and its Western backers over the talks will be a sign of trouble. European diplomats have been pressing Ukraine to keep their ambitions in check for the talks and pushed back against some of Kyiv&#39;s proposals, including its hope to win backing among developing countries for imposing sanctions on Russia. Several Western diplomats said after the Copenhagen talks that the degree of Ukraine&#39;s flexibility will be make or break for the talks.</p><p> Write to Laurence Norman at <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 13:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-saudi-arabias-ukraine-peace-talks-how-to-measure-success-fedb58ea</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-saudi-arabias-ukraine-peace-talks-how-to-measure-success-fedb58ea<author><![CDATA[Laurence Norman]]></author><category> ukraine</category><category> wsjworld</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israeli Reservists Start Missing Duty, Threatening Military Unity and Readiness]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Refusal to serve is one of the starkest examples of how the push to remake the judiciary has torn the country apart <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106909"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828271?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Israeli Air Force cadets at a graduation ceremony. Flight training has been disrupted by protests among instructors.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ariel Schalit/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106909"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dov Lieber</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 6:50 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-threatening-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> TEL AVIV—Col. Nissim Yogev spent 25 years as a combat flight navigator in the Israeli Air Force, where he fought in Israel&#39;s war with Lebanon and saw his best friend go missing in combat, never to return. Last week, he said he made the hardest decision of his life when, with tears streaming down his face, he wrote to his commander that he would stop reporting for volunteer reserve duty, where he trained cadets at the air force&#39;s only flight school.</p><p> “The flight school will probably be OK without me, but I cannot be OK with myself as long as things continue this way,” he wrote.</p><p> When Yogev, 64, missed his first day of teaching last week he was following through on a threat from thousands of volunteer military reservists like him to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">suspend their service</a> after Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s coalition <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">passed the first part</a> of an effort to limit the power of the Supreme Court.</p><p> The reservists say <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the legislation</a> undermines Israel&#39;s liberal democracy, breaking the social contract for which they have put their lives at risk. Brothers in Arms, one of the largest groups organizing the push for refusing to serve, said there are already thousands of others like Yogev who have withheld their reserve duty service. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828288?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Col. Nissim Yogev, in white shirt, with a friend who went missing in action in 1986.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nissim Yogev</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> It is unclear how many reservists like Yogev have already missed days they were supposed to be in service. But there are signs that the military is already feeling the loss. In at least one recent pilot-training course, almost none of the instructors showed up for duty, said a person familiar with the matter. The issue became so acute that the head of the flight-training school sent a letter last week to parents of cadets to say that training was continuing, despite the fact that a number of instructors hadn&#39;t shown up.</p><p> Netanyahu has said the reservist protest is undemocratic; that soldiers are trying to dictate policy to the government. Some in his coalition have called it an attempted military coup. The coalition says it is enacting policies favored by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its voters</a> who say <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-government-looks-at-next-steps-in-judicial-overhaul-shrugging-off-protests-7172e0ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the top court</a> is controlled by liberal justices who too quickly overturn the will of the people. The legislation, they say, is aimed at restoring a proper balance of power between the different branches of government.</p><p> The reservists&#39; protest is one of the starkest examples of how Netanyahu&#39;s push to remake the judiciary has torn the country apart. Israel&#39;s army has long been a unifying force for a divided society and is essential for a country that has been embroiled in conflicts since its founding 75 years ago.</p><p> An erosion of unity could harm the people&#39;s army model on which Israel&#39;s military is based, which has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-israel-army-service-is-required-for-all-that-could-now-change-2c76624d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">already come under pressure</a> in recent years. It could also harm the military in more immediate ways, affecting operational readiness if reservists&#39; skills become outdated. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828273?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has pushed ahead with judicial overhauls despite large-scale protests.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: AMIR COHEN/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “The damage to fitness is limited, but there is a possibility of damage to fitness in the long term,” said Israeli Defense Minister Yoav Gallant in a parliamentary committee meeting this week.</p><p> Also this week, Israel&#39;s military chief of staff held group meetings with every single officer ranked colonel and above to talk about how to deal with political disagreement within the military, as the divisions seep into the regular ranks.</p><p> Israel&#39;s military has hundreds of thousands of reservists, some 120,000 of whom are in active reserve duty between the ages of 22 and 45, according to statements by a senior military officer in May of 2022. Those above the age of active reserve duty can continue to volunteer for reserve duty, and some—like Yogev—hold positions that require their service on a weekly or biweekly basis and have their days of duty scheduled in advance.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What impact will the protest by air force flight instructors have on judicial overhaul in Israel?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Flight-academy instructors such as Yogev sign up months in advance for teaching slots, and are also expected to come in on short notice when needed. He said he missed his first day of teaching at the end of July and won&#39;t show up for his next scheduled teaching day in mid-August.</p><p> Eyal Naveh, 47, a reservist officer in Israel&#39;s most elite commando unit, Sayeret Matkal, and a leader of the Brothers in Arms protest organization, said the group now has a list of thousands of reservists who have signed letters to commanders or told them in person that they won&#39;t be reporting for duty. Naveh said they include intelligence and cyber specialists, as well as members of the naval reservist command. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828279?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Israeli reservists sign a declaration refusing to serve during a protest in Tel Aviv.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Eyal Warshavsky/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Most concerning for the military is the hundreds of air-force reservists who have put their service on pause. Reservist protest leaders say that includes hundreds of active fighter pilots, drone operators, navigators and instructors. Unlike most reservists, air-force volunteers serve on a regular basis and are a pillar of the air force, itself a backbone of national security.</p><p> Many veteran reservists from air-force headquarters have suspended their service, said Naveh, although he couldn&#39;t provide specific numbers. They are called in to advise sometimes on regular operations and are crucial for the military during wartime.</p><p> “The reserve pilots are a cornerstone of the Air Force&#39;s operational ability to reach its goals, and their contribution to Israel&#39;s security is significant,” the Israeli military said when asked about the hundreds of air-force reservists refusing to serve. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-threatening-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Israel&#39;s doctors went on strike on Tuesday and authorities forcibly removed protesters from roadways during a night of unrest over a judicial overhaul carried out by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s government. Photo: Amir Levy/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“At present, the Air Force is fully capable and ready to operate. Failure to report for an extended period may put the [Israel Defense Forces] and the Air Force in a state of decreased competence and readiness for war.”</p><p> The Israeli military declined to comment when asked how many reservists have suspended their service.</p><p> Over time, the absences will impact the training schedule of Israel&#39;s air-force cadets, say instructors who have suspended their service. The majority of instructors are reservists with decades of experience, and there is no clear replacement for them, they say. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="1136" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828322?width=639&amp;height=1136" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Brig. Gen. Offer Lapidot wears a T-shirt reading, “Dictatorship? No way.”</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Offer Lapidot</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Brig. Gen. Offer Lapidot, 73, a former commander of the Air Force Academy, said there aren&#39;t enough regular service instructors for all of the cadets without major assistance from the reservists.</p><p> After spending his entire adult life in the air force, largely as a fighter pilot and commander, and until recently as an instructor, Lapidot sent his suspension-of-service letter to his commander a week and a half before Netanyahu&#39;s government passed the first judicial legislation. He said he had hoped to apply enough pressure to stop the bill from passing.</p><p> He said he has been forced to weigh “the safety of the country, versus the very existence of the country that we fought and were ready to give our lives for.”</p><p> Zur Allon, 46, a tech CEO and frequent reservist with the artillery special forces, has suspended his service, though he hasn&#39;t been asked to report for duty since doing so two weeks ago. In case of a national emergency, he said he would report for duty. But he worries about how a long pause might impact the military&#39;s readiness for battle.</p><p> “It is like a car: Leave it in the garage for a year and it won&#39;t work,” he said.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ari Flanzraich contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Dov Lieber at <a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 10:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-threatening-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-threatening-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category> Air Force</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Armed Forces</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> air force</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>armed forces</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Latest Problem: People Don’t Want to Go There]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> As geopolitical tensions rise, fewer visitors are traveling to the world&#39;s No. 2 economy, widening the East-West divide <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827041?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Shanghai airport was sparsely populated recently, with far fewer people arriving to China from overseas trips organized by travel agencies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Raul Ariano/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">Wenxin Fan</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Half a year after China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-xi-jinping-reversed-his-zero-covid-policy-in-china-11672853171?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">lifted Covid-19 restrictions</a> and reopened its borders, few international travelers are coming—another sign of decoupling between China and the West that could have negative repercussions for a long time.</p><p> Foreign travelers&#39; absence is particularly evident in major cities like Beijing and Shanghai, where the numbers of foreigners who visited in the first half of the year totaled less than a quarter of comparable figures in 2019, before the Covid pandemic.</p><p> Nationwide, just 52,000 people arrived to mainland China from overseas on trips organized by travel agencies during the first quarter, the latest period for which national data is available, compared with 3.7 million in the first quarter of 2019. As in past years, nearly half of the visitors came from the self-ruled island of Taiwan and the Chinese territories of Hong Kong and Macau, rather than farther-away places like the US or Europe.</p><p> “The number of visitors from Europe, America, Japan and Korea are all dropping, substantially,” said Xiao Qianhui, a director with the semiofficial China Tourism Association in a speech in May.</p><p> Fewer tourists and businesspeople from overseas means fewer opportunities for foreigners to see China with their own eyes and interact with locals, an important factor in reducing geopolitical tensions, experts say.</p><p> The dearth of visitors could also be contributing to less investment in China. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Foreign direct investment into the country fell</a> to $20 billion in the first quarter, compared with $100 billion in last year&#39;s first quarter, according to an analysis of government figures by Mark Witzke at Rhodium Group, a research firm. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A mausoleum in Nanjing was swarmed with tourists in 2019, before the Covid pandemic hit.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Su Yang/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The drop in foreign investment and arrivals comes as China&#39;s economy stagnates, with a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">depressed housing market</a> , youth <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">unemployment</a> at record highs and widening fears the country could be <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">slipping into deflation.</a> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">Chinese economy barely grew</a> in the second quarter from the first three months of the year.</p><p> A <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8" target="_blank" class="icon none">shortage of available flights</a> to China is partly to blame for the low arrival numbers, with carriers not yet restoring the same level of service they offered pre-Covid. But Chinese and overseas tourism experts say foreign visitors are also staying away because of deteriorating relations between China and the West, which has made them more wary of visiting.</p><p> In June, the US government issued a travel advisory warning Americans to reconsider travel to mainland China due to what it called “the arbitrary enforcement of local laws,” including exit bans and the possibility of wrongful detentions.</p><p> Matt Kelly, a Boston-based business consultant, said he has fond memories of his trip 15 years ago cycling around Guilin, a picturesque hilly city in southern China. He visited China two more times, but said he had no interest in going back today.</p><p> “Would I go back to that China I knew?是的！”他说。 But now, “China does seem to portray itself as very anti-Western, anti-American, specifically. It makes me very uneasy.”</p><p> Friendly Planet Travel, a Pennsylvania-based boutique operator, used to send as many as 1,500 tourists to China a year. Since Covid, it hasn&#39;t had a single request, said Peggy Goldman, its founder and president. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828850?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Matt Kelly in Guilin, China, in 2008.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Matt Kelly</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> When her team researched the destinations people are searching for online, “China is really at the bottom of that tracking,” she said. “There was a lot of animosity around the subject of China.”</p><p> The company has yet to put its China packages back online, although Goldman said she believes China will become popular again eventually.</p><p> Leisure travel from North America to China in the first half of 2023 was about 40% of the same period of 2019, according to Mondee Holdings, a travel technology company based in Austin. Mondee sold about half a million flights from North America to China in 2019 through travel agents and other intermediaries, roughly one-fifth of all air travel from North America to China that year.</p><p> Although business executives are still making inquiries about traveling to China, many now are focusing on risks, whereas in the past, they wanted to find out how to expedite a visa, said Dan Harris, a partner in Seattle at Harris Bricken, a law firm that advises on investments in China.</p><p> “Companies are very, very concerned about their people going to China. Why wouldn&#39;t they be?” he said, pointing to news of China&#39;s recent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreign-firms-in-china-squeezed-by-u-s-disclosure-demands-beijings-security-clampdown-658ef8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">investigations into Western due-diligence and other firms</a> , which included government raids on global consultancies including Bain &amp; Co. “People are not going to China unless they have to.”</p><p> Harris, who used to go to China frequently for work in Beijing, with stops for beer and seafood in Qingdao, said he has told some executives their risks would be low. But he has himself stopped going, after becoming vocally critical of the Chinese government in recent years.</p><p> China&#39;s Ministry of Culture and Tourism didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> Chinese officials have held meetings with business associations from the US, Europe and Japan recently <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to reassure them</a> the country still welcomes foreign investment. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827025?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tourist visits to Zhangjiajie National Park have plummeted from 2019.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Wu Yongbing/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> China&#39;s ambassador to the US, Xie Feng, said at the Aspen Security Forum in July that tourists of both countries should visit each other. He suggested hosting a tourism forum and increasing the number of flights, and called on Washington to adjust its travel advisory.</p><p> The absence of foreign visitors won&#39;t hurt China the same way it would places like Thailand or Iceland, whose economies rely heavily on tourists. Chinese travelers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-travelers-swarm-domestic-tourist-sites-a-positive-sign-for-economy-f45c4977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are now spending more on domestic tourism</a> than they did in 2019.</p><p> Still, there are many businesses in China that do count on visitors. The lack of them represents a lost opportunity for China to show itself in a more positive light to foreigners.</p><p> Central China&#39;s Zhangjiajie National Park, a region of striking rock formations where the “floating mountains” in the movie Avatar were filmed, recorded only 25,600 overseas visitors through mid-May, compared with 500,000 in the first five months of 2019.</p><p> Snow Yu, a Shanghai tourist guide, used to do a thriving business showing foreigners around, including acting as a guide for executives of the Golden State Warriors and Georgia Tech&#39;s Yellow Jackets basketball team in 2017. During the pandemic, when borders were largely closed, he took a temporary job tutoring English.</p><p> Yu has returned to his old job, leading mostly local tour groups. But they don&#39;t need his English skills and give fewer tips. As a result, he says his income is down by nearly half from before the pandemic. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5BD0F48A-0DA4-4CED-8A69-018103B38E36&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> President Biden said on Sunday he sees a potential thaw in relations between the US and China, in a news conference wrapping up the G-7 meeting in Japan. Photo: Susan Walsh/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“The world needs to be connected,” he said, adding that English-speaking visitors from neighboring countries are beginning to come back.</p><p> The drop in visitors from the West and parts of East Asia has been offset in part by an increase in the number of Russians arriving, though Chinese travel experts say they spend less.</p><p> In June, when Zhangjiajie, the national park, invited more than 80 international tourism agents to town, a majority came from Russia. Local officials promised to add more flights from China&#39;s northern neighbor or extend existing flights from other Chinese cities.</p><p> In his speech, Xiao, the tourism official, appealed for more support from the central government. He stressed that inbound tourism could help defuse geopolitical tensions “in ways similar to &#39;ping pong diplomacy,&#39;” referring to exchanges of table-tennis players in the 1970s that helped thaw relations between China and the US</p><p> He cited a recent China visit by Elon Musk&#39;s mother, who posted positive messages about her experience on Instagram.</p><p> Another group that is steering clear of China is expatriates, who in previous years acted as bridges between Chinese society and their respective home countries. Many invited family and friends to visit.</p><p> Investment consultant Alexander Sirakov, 37, moved back to his home country Bulgaria from Shanghai last August. He said that most people in his wider circle of expatriate friends also departed, including eight out of the 10 expat families living in his compound.</p><p> “People now perceive China as very distant and somewhat alienated,” he said. “It was exactly the opposite four years ago, when China was really open and vibrant, a must-go place.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Liyan Qi contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Wenxin Fan at <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Respiratory Tract Diseases</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Novel Coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>respiratory tract diseases</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治</category><category>novel coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>travel </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Real Reason You’re Having a Hard Time Getting Things Done at the Office]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Working from home altered our brains. We need more office time to fix them. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828457/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Sam Kelly/The Wall Street Journal, iStock (11) <span>Photo Illustration by Sam Kelly/The Wall Street Journal, iStock (11)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ray-a-smith" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ray A. Smith</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> If you still don&#39;t have your office groove back, there might be a scientific explanation. Hybrid work arrangements mess with our brains.</p><p> Frustrated bosses who survey their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-return-to-office-rate-rises-above-50-for-first-time-since-pandemic-began-11675285071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">half-empty officescapes</a> say it makes no sense that somebody who worked full time in an office before 2020 can&#39;t show up like they used to. But neurologists and behavioral scientists say the collective amnesia for effectively working alongside each other makes perfect sense to them.</p><p> Some workers have lost the muscle memory in their minds required to get jobs done in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-open-office-is-out-seated-privacy-is-in-as-cubicles-make-a-comeback-11663189508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">an open-office setting</a> and, like flabby biceps, that muscle has to be exercised to strengthen, says S. Thomas Carmichael, professor and chair of the neurology department at UCLA&#39;s David Geffen School of Medicine.</p><p> After years of remote work, our brains&#39; selective attention skills and ability to block out distractions is weakened, Carmichael says. Those who prefer to work from home might not like one of his remedies: Make yourself work from the office more often.</p><p> “The brain is really good at understanding contingencies, so if we just say &#39;I&#39;ll just get this done when I&#39;m at home,&#39; we don&#39;t learn it as well,” he says.</p><h3> Drowning in a sea of &#39;what ifs?&#39;</h3><p> Knowing how effective working from home can be has created a simmering unhappiness, says organizational psychologist Cathleen Swody. Many workers lose their uninterrupted autonomy in social office spaces. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828332?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Maryia Babinova says even small office time wasters have become a major annoyance.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Maryia Babinova</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Maryia Babinova, a senior software engineer in New York City, tried going into her office several days a week back in 2021 and found it nearly impossible to be productive.</p><p> “The first 30 to 45 minutes of my day were taken up by saying hello to everybody,” she says.</p><p> Babinova says even small office time wasters have become a major annoyance. A trip to the office coffee machine, for instance, can take as long as 15 minutes when there&#39;s a line. At home, she says, caffeine is at her fingertips, keeping her on task.</p><p> Now, Babinova only shows up in person when her team members visit from another city. At the office, she works on tasks that don&#39;t require a heavy mental lift so she can get them done.</p><p> Constantly comparing 2023&#39;s office realities with alternative remote-work setups can add to workers&#39; readjustment woes, says Laura M. Giurge, an assistant professor at the London School of Economics, who teaches a course on the science of time at work.</p><p> When people start to ponder what life would be like if their circumstances were different, they can rapidly end up drowning in a sea of “what ifs,” a psychological concept known as counterfactual thinking.</p><p> “Now, when we go to the office, we have the counterfactuals of our home offices,” Giurge says. “We know how much better things would be…how much more work we might get done.”</p><p> It&#39;s hard to un-remember how nice it was <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to take the dog for a walk midday</a> , or how helpful it was to log out at 4 pm to get dinner started and log back in later. Running through scenarios of how time could be better spent takes up precious brainpower, distracting us from the real work at hand, psychologists say. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> With housing in short supply, developers are converting more empty offices into apartments. But not all buildings are candidates for reuse, even as more than 1 billion square feet of office space sits vacant across the US Photo Illustration: Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>Unsettling quiet</h3><p> Getting used to working with background noise takes time.</p><p> Many workplaces are quieter now because they are less crowded, and that means there can be periods of dead silence punctuated by sudden noise that feels magnified, jarring people again and again all day long. Even toggling between work-from-home solitude one day to a noisy office the next can have a similar effect.</p><p> “We have to habituate ourselves to all those distractions all over again in order to get any good work done,” says Vanessa Bohns, a professor of organizational behavior at Cornell University. She points to research that shows it takes 20 minutes to get used to background noise, but five minutes of silence before bringing back the noise forces the brain&#39;s process to start over again.</p><p> Many workers and a few bosses now view the office as a place to collaborate, but not the only place to do head-down individual work.</p><p> In a large-scale survey published by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">Microsoft</a> last year, 84% of employees cited connecting with co-workers as their key motivation for working in person. More than 70% said they would go to the office more frequently if they knew their direct team members or work friends would be there.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you find it harder to get work done in the office than you did before the pandemic? Why, or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “The data shows we can&#39;t only see the office as a place to get focused work done,” said Colette Stallbaumer, Microsoft&#39;s general manager of Future of Work.</p><p> Lynn Dang, a software developer in the Dallas area, uses her three mandatory office days for face-to-face meetings and work that doesn&#39;t require intense concentration.</p><p> When she transitioned back to the office last year, she noticed she couldn&#39;t concentrate on reading code like she could while working from home. Loud team discussions and overhearing one-sided conversations amid the cubicles from people who were on the phone or dialed into video meetings created a constant assault on her senses.</p><p> “It was like I&#39;m gonna have to find something to do on my to-do list that would make me productive,” she says. “Otherwise I&#39;m going to have to keep working overtime or working over the weekend just to get stuff done.”</p><p> Write to Ray A. Smith at <a href="mailto:Ray.Smith@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Ray.Smith@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1<author><![CDATA[Ray A. Smith]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> S. Thomas Carmichael</category><category> Cathleen Swody</category><category> Laura M. Giurge</category><category> Vanessa Bohns</category><category> Colette Stallbaumer</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Latest Problem: People Don’t Want to Go There]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> As geopolitical tensions rise, fewer visitors are traveling to the world&#39;s No. 2 economy, widening the East-West divide <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827041?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Shanghai airport was sparsely populated recently, with far fewer people arriving to China from overseas trips organized by travel agencies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Raul Ariano/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">Wenxin Fan</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Half a year after China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-xi-jinping-reversed-his-zero-covid-policy-in-china-11672853171?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">lifted Covid-19 restrictions</a> and reopened its borders, few international travelers are coming—another sign of decoupling between China and the West that could have negative repercussions for a long time.</p><p> Foreign travelers&#39; absence is particularly evident in major cities like Beijing and Shanghai, where the numbers of foreigners who visited in the first half of the year totaled less than a quarter of comparable figures in 2019, before the Covid pandemic.</p><p> Nationwide, just 52,000 people arrived to mainland China from overseas on trips organized by travel agencies during the first quarter, the latest period for which national data is available, compared with 3.7 million in the first quarter of 2019. As in past years, nearly half of the visitors came from the self-ruled island of Taiwan and the Chinese territories of Hong Kong and Macau, rather than farther-away places like the US or Europe.</p><p> “The number of visitors from Europe, America, Japan and Korea are all dropping, substantially,” said Xiao Qianhui, a director with the semiofficial China Tourism Association in a speech in May.</p><p> Fewer tourists and businesspeople from overseas means fewer opportunities for foreigners to see China with their own eyes and interact with locals, an important factor in reducing geopolitical tensions, experts say.</p><p> The dearth of visitors could also be contributing to less investment in China. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Foreign direct investment into the country fell</a> to $20 billion in the first quarter, compared with $100 billion in last year&#39;s first quarter, according to an analysis of government figures by Mark Witzke at Rhodium Group, a research firm. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A mausoleum in Nanjing was swarmed with tourists in 2019, before the Covid pandemic hit.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Su Yang/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The drop in foreign investment and arrivals comes as China&#39;s economy stagnates, with a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">depressed housing market</a> , youth <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">unemployment</a> at record highs and widening fears the country could be <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">slipping into deflation.</a> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">Chinese economy barely grew</a> in the second quarter from the first three months of the year.</p><p> A <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8" target="_blank" class="icon none">shortage of available flights</a> to China is partly to blame for the low arrival numbers, with carriers not yet restoring the same level of service they offered pre-Covid. But Chinese and overseas tourism experts say foreign visitors are also staying away because of deteriorating relations between China and the West, which has made them more wary of visiting.</p><p> In June, the US government issued a travel advisory warning Americans to reconsider travel to mainland China due to what it called “the arbitrary enforcement of local laws,” including exit bans and the possibility of wrongful detentions.</p><p> Matt Kelly, a Boston-based business consultant, said he has fond memories of his trip 15 years ago cycling around Guilin, a picturesque hilly city in southern China. He visited China two more times, but said he had no interest in going back today.</p><p> “Would I go back to that China I knew?是的！”他说。 But now, “China does seem to portray itself as very anti-Western, anti-American, specifically. It makes me very uneasy.”</p><p> Friendly Planet Travel, a Pennsylvania-based boutique operator, used to send as many as 1,500 tourists to China a year. Since Covid, it hasn&#39;t had a single request, said Peggy Goldman, its founder and president. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828850?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Matt Kelly in Guilin, China, in 2008.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Matt Kelly</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> When her team researched the destinations people are searching for online, “China is really at the bottom of that tracking,” she said. “There was a lot of animosity around the subject of China.”</p><p> The company has yet to put its China packages back online, although Goldman said she believes China will become popular again eventually.</p><p> Leisure travel from North America to China in the first half of 2023 was about 40% of the same period of 2019, according to Mondee Holdings, a travel technology company based in Austin. Mondee sold about half a million flights from North America to China in 2019 through travel agents and other intermediaries, roughly one-fifth of all air travel from North America to China that year.</p><p> Although business executives are still making inquiries about traveling to China, many now are focusing on risks, whereas in the past, they wanted to find out how to expedite a visa, said Dan Harris, a partner in Seattle at Harris Bricken, a law firm that advises on investments in China.</p><p> “Companies are very, very concerned about their people going to China. Why wouldn&#39;t they be?” he said, pointing to news of China&#39;s recent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreign-firms-in-china-squeezed-by-u-s-disclosure-demands-beijings-security-clampdown-658ef8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">investigations into Western due-diligence and other firms</a> , which included government raids on global consultancies including Bain &amp; Co. “People are not going to China unless they have to.”</p><p> Harris, who used to go to China frequently for work in Beijing, with stops for beer and seafood in Qingdao, said he has told some executives their risks would be low. But he has himself stopped going, after becoming vocally critical of the Chinese government in recent years.</p><p> China&#39;s Ministry of Culture and Tourism didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> Chinese officials have held meetings with business associations from the US, Europe and Japan recently <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to reassure them</a> the country still welcomes foreign investment. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827025?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tourist visits to Zhangjiajie National Park have plummeted from 2019.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Wu Yongbing/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> China&#39;s ambassador to the US, Xie Feng, said at the Aspen Security Forum in July that tourists of both countries should visit each other. He suggested hosting a tourism forum and increasing the number of flights, and called on Washington to adjust its travel advisory.</p><p> The absence of foreign visitors won&#39;t hurt China the same way it would places like Thailand or Iceland, whose economies rely heavily on tourists. Chinese travelers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-travelers-swarm-domestic-tourist-sites-a-positive-sign-for-economy-f45c4977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are now spending more on domestic tourism</a> than they did in 2019.</p><p> Still, there are many businesses in China that do count on visitors. The lack of them represents a lost opportunity for China to show itself in a more positive light to foreigners.</p><p> Central China&#39;s Zhangjiajie National Park, a region of striking rock formations where the “floating mountains” in the movie Avatar were filmed, recorded only 25,600 overseas visitors through mid-May, compared with 500,000 in the first five months of 2019.</p><p> Snow Yu, a Shanghai tourist guide, used to do a thriving business showing foreigners around, including acting as a guide for executives of the Golden State Warriors and Georgia Tech&#39;s Yellow Jackets basketball team in 2017. During the pandemic, when borders were largely closed, he took a temporary job tutoring English.</p><p> Yu has returned to his old job, leading mostly local tour groups. But they don&#39;t need his English skills and give fewer tips. As a result, he says his income is down by nearly half from before the pandemic. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5BD0F48A-0DA4-4CED-8A69-018103B38E36&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> President Biden said on Sunday he sees a potential thaw in relations between the US and China, in a news conference wrapping up the G-7 meeting in Japan. Photo: Susan Walsh/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“The world needs to be connected,” he said, adding that English-speaking visitors from neighboring countries are beginning to come back.</p><p> The drop in visitors from the West and parts of East Asia has been offset in part by an increase in the number of Russians arriving, though Chinese travel experts say they spend less.</p><p> In June, when Zhangjiajie, the national park, invited more than 80 international tourism agents to town, a majority came from Russia. Local officials promised to add more flights from China&#39;s northern neighbor or extend existing flights from other Chinese cities.</p><p> In his speech, Xiao, the tourism official, appealed for more support from the central government. He stressed that inbound tourism could help defuse geopolitical tensions “in ways similar to &#39;ping pong diplomacy,&#39;” referring to exchanges of table-tennis players in the 1970s that helped thaw relations between China and the US</p><p> He cited a recent China visit by Elon Musk&#39;s mother, who posted positive messages about her experience on Instagram.</p><p> Another group that is steering clear of China is expatriates, who in previous years acted as bridges between Chinese society and their respective home countries. Many invited family and friends to visit.</p><p> Investment consultant Alexander Sirakov, 37, moved back to his home country Bulgaria from Shanghai last August. He said that most people in his wider circle of expatriate friends also departed, including eight out of the 10 expat families living in his compound.</p><p> “People now perceive China as very distant and somewhat alienated,” he said. “It was exactly the opposite four years ago, when China was really open and vibrant, a must-go place.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Liyan Qi contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Wenxin Fan at <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Respiratory Tract Diseases</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Novel Coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>respiratory tract diseases</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治</category><category>novel coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>travel</category></item></channel></rss>